# CTF: Mutation Station

> **Category:** Rev/Pwn
> **Attack Pattern:** [CAPEC-28: Fuzzing](https://capec.mitre.org/data/definitions/28.html)
> **Flag format:** `itc266{...}`
> **Estimated time:** 20–40 minutes after completing the walkthrough

---

## Story

A sloppy intern at a fictional IoT company shipped a record-processing utility called `station` with their device firmware. Their QA department tested "normal" inputs and declared it safe. Your job is to prove them wrong.

The binary accepts a single positional argument — the path to an input file. Records follow a rigid little binary protocol. Surface inspection will tell you what shape the envelope has to be; finding the bug means fuzzing *inside* that envelope until the processor breaks. When it breaks, it confesses.

## Files

| File | Purpose |
|------|---------|
| `station` | The target binary (Linux x86-64, stripped) |
| `sample_input.bin` | A valid record — a known-good seed for mutation |
| `Makefile` | For rebuilding if you want to (you probably don't need to) |
| `station.c` | **Do not read this until you've solved it.** Source is included for grading; peeking is self-defeating. |

## Rules of Engagement

1. You must trigger the flag using **fuzzing**. Reverse-engineering the binary to extract the flag statically defeats the purpose of the exercise.
2. You may use any mutation or generation fuzzer (radamsa, Python, boofuzz, AFL++ — all fine).
3. The flag prints to stdout when the right thing happens. You'll know it when you see it.

## Getting Started

```bash
# Make sure the binary runs at all
./station sample_input.bin
# → accepted record (15 bytes)

# Try something obviously wrong
echo "random junk" > bad.bin
./station bad.bin
# → rejected: bad magic

# Now think. What did that error tell you?
```

